.TH QSP-AGENT 1 "June 2026" "qsp-agent 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
qsp-agent \- expose a radio transceiver through the QSP signaling service
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B qsp-agent
[\fB-c\fR, \fB--config\fR \fICONFIG_PATH\fR]
[\fB-d\fR, \fB--daemon\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B qsp-agent
is the QSP hardware agent. It connects a locally attached transceiver to remote
clients through the QSP signaling server and WebRTC.
.PP
When managed by systemd, the service should run in the foreground. The packaged
unit uses:
.PP
.B /usr/bin/qsp-agent --config /etc/qsp-agent/config.toml
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR -c ", " --config " " \fICONFIG_PATH\fR
Load the application configuration from the provided TOML file.
.TP
.BR -d ", " --daemon
Detach into the background. This option is intended for manual Unix daemon use
and should not be used from systemd.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/qsp-agent/config.toml
System-wide configuration file installed by the Debian package.
.TP
.B /lib/systemd/system/qsp-agent.service
Systemd unit file installed by the Debian package.
.TP
.B /run/qsp-agent/qsp-agent.pid
PID file path used by the packaged configuration.
.TP
.B /run/qsp-agent/qsp-agent.lock
Lock file path used by the packaged configuration.
.SH SYSTEMD
Enable and start the service with:
.PP
.EX
systemctl enable --now qsp-agent.service
.EE
.PP
Logs are written to journald and can be viewed with:
.PP
.EX
journalctl -u qsp-agent.service
.EE
.SH AUTHOR
Florian MAZEN
